11 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
12 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
13 Article – Education
14 7–11A–01.
15 (a) In this subtitle the following words have the meanings indicated.
16 (b) “Behavior intervention plan” has the meaning stated in § 7–1101 of this title.
17 (c) “Elopement” means the act of a student leaving the school campus without the
18 permission of a school staff member who has responsibility for the student.
19 (d) “IEP” means an individualized education program as defined under the
20 federal Individuals with Disabilities Education Act.
21 (e) “Nonpublic school” has the meaning stated in § 7–1101 of this title.
22 (f) “School” means:
23 (1) A public elementary, middle, or high school;
24 (2) The Maryland School for the Blind;
25 (3) The Maryland School for the Deaf; and
26 (4) A nonpublic school.
27 (g) “School campus” means the buildings and grounds of a school, including a
28 playground.
29 (h) (1) “Wandering” means the act of a student leaving a classroom or area on
30 the school campus, but not leaving the school campus, without the permission of a school
31 staff member who has responsibility for the student.

HOUSE BILL 1182 3
1 (2) “Wandering” does not include a student leaving a classroom or area on
2 the school campus under a flash pass or another standing arrangement that has been
3 approved by a school administrator.
4 7–11A–02.
5 (a) Each time a student attempts or accomplishes an elopement, the school shall
6 notify the student’s parent or guardian of the elopement incident on the same day as the
7 elopement incident.
8 (b) At least one time each year, a school or a student’s IEP team shall review and
9 address with relevant stakeholders a student’s wandering or elopement behavior in
10 updating the student’s IEP or behavior intervention plan.
11 (C) A SCHOOL SHALL DEVELOP POLICIES AND PROCEDURES TO IMPLEMENT
12 THE REQUIREMENTS OF THIS SECTION.
13 [7–11A–03.
14 A school shall develop policies and procedures to implement the requirements of this
15 subtitle.]
16 7–11A–03.
17 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “LOCATIVE DEVICE” MEANS A WEARABLE OR
18 PORTABLE ELECTRONIC DEVICE THAT IS CAPABLE OF LOCATING A STUDENT
19 DURING AN ELOPEMENT INCIDENT.
20 (B) SUBJECT TO SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION, A SCHOOL MAY
21 COORDINATE A STUDENT’S VOLUNTARY USE OF A LOCATIVE DEVICE AND MONITOR
22 THE STUDENT’S LOCATION USING THE LOCATIVE DEVICE ONLY IF:
23 (1) THE STUDENT HAS A DOCUMENTED HISTORY OF WANDERING OR
24 ELOPEMENT BEHAVIOR IN THE STUDENT’S IEP OR BEHAVIOR INTERVENTION PLAN;
25 AND
26 (2) THE STUDENT’S PARENT OR GUARDIAN PROVIDES INFORMED,
27 WRITTEN CONSENT TO:
28 (I) THE STUDENT’S VOLUNTARY USE OF THE LOCATIVE
29 DEVICE; AND
30 (II) THE SCHOOL’S MONITORING OF THE STUDENT’S LOCATION
31 USING THE LOCATIVE DEVICE; AND

4 HOUSE BILL 1182
1 (3) THE LOCATIVE DEVICE:
2 (I) IS INCAPABLE OF MAKING AUDIO OR VIDEO RECORDINGS OF
3 OTHER STUDENTS OR SCHOOL PERSONNEL; OR
4 (II) HAS FEATURES CAPABLE OF AUDIO OR VIDEO RECORDING
5 TURNED OFF WHEN THE STUDENT IS IN AN EDUCATIONAL SETTING.
6 (C) (1) A SCHOOL MAY MONITOR A STUDENT’S LOCATION USING A
7 LOCATIVE DEVICE UNDER THIS SECTION ONLY FOR WANDERING OR ELOPEMENT
8 BEHAVIOR.
9 (2) A SCHOOL SHALL:
10 (I) LIMIT INFORMATION OBTAINED THROUGH A STUDENT’S
11 VOLUNTARY USE OF A LOCATIVE DEVICE IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SECTION TO
12 INFORMATION THAT IS REASONABLY NECESSARY TO ADDRESS OR RESPOND TO A
13 STUDENT’S WANDERING OR ELOPEMENT BEHAVIOR; AND
14 (II) MAINTAIN ANY INFORMATION OBTAINED THROUGH A
15 STUDENT’S USE OF A LOCATIVE DEVICE IN ACCORDANCE WITH APPLICABLE
16 FEDERAL AND STATE EDUCATION PRIVACY LAWS.
17 (3) INFORMATION OBTAINED THROUGH A STUDENT’S VOLUNTARY
18 USE OF A LOCATIVE DEVICE IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SECTION:
19 (I) MAY BE ACCESSED ONLY BY:
20 1. PERSONNEL IDENTIFIED IN THE STUDENT’S IEP OR
21 BEHAVIOR INTERVENTION PLAN; AND
22 2. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROVIDERS AS NECESSARY
23 DURING AN ELOPEMENT INCIDENT;
24 (II) MAY NOT BE RETAINED FOR LONGER THAN NECESSARY TO
25 ADDRESS OR RESPOND TO A STUDENT’S WANDERING OR ELOPEMENT BEHAVIOR OR
26 AS REQUIRED BY LAW; AND
27 (III) SHALL BE PROTECTED BY EMPLOYING REASONABLE
28 ADMINISTRATIVE, TECHNICAL, AND PHYSICAL SAFEGUARDS.
29 (D) (1) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ISSUE ADVISORY GUIDANCE TO
30 SCHOOLS ON:

HOUSE BILL 1182 5
1 (I) INCORPORATING A STUDENT’S VOLUNTARY USE OF A
2 LOCATIVE DEVICE IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SECTION IN THE STUDENT’S IEP OR
3 BEHAVIOR INTERVENTION PLAN; AND
4 (II) PRIVACY AND DATA PROTECTION CONSIDERATIONS
5 ASSOCIATED WITH USE OF A LOCATIVE DEVICE.
6 (2) THE DEPARTMENT’S GUIDANCE UNDER THIS SUBSECTION SHALL:
7 (I) SHALL GRANT A SCHOOL DISCRETION AS TO WHETHER AND
8 HOW TO IMPLEMENT A STUDENT’S VOLUNTARY USE OF A LOCATIVE DEVICE IN
9 ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SECTION; AND
10 (II) MAY NOT BE CONSTRUED AS LEGAL ADVICE ABOUT THE
11 FEDERAL ADMINISTRATION OF FEDERAL PRIVACY LAW.
12 (E) A SCHOOL MAY DEVELOP POLICIES AND PROCEDURES TO IMPLEMENT
13 THE REQUIREMENTS OF THIS SECTION.
14 (F) NOTHING IN THIS SECTION MAY BE CONSTRUED TO:
15 (1) REQUIRE A SCHOOL TO PROVIDE, PURCHASE, REIMBURSE,
16 MANAGE, OR MONITOR A LOCATIVE DEVICE OR A RELATED SERVICE PLAN; OR
17 (2) REQUIRE A PARENT, GUARDIAN, OR STUDENT TO PURCHASE OR
18 USE A LOCATIVE DEVICE, INCLUDING AS A CONDITION OF ENROLLMENT IN A SCHOOL
19 OR FOR THE PROVISION OF ANY SERVICE.
20 7–11A–04.
21 A SCHOOL:
22 (1) SUBJECT TO ITEM (2) OF THIS SECTION, SHALL DEVELOP
23 POLICIES AND PROCEDURES TO IMPLEMENT THE REQUIREMENTS OF THIS
24 SUBTITLE; AND
25 (2) MAY DEVELOP POLICIES AND PROCEDURES TO IMPLEMENT THE
26 REQUIREMENTS OF § 7–11A–03 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
27 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
28 1, 2026.

